# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uefi-firmware
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Mebromi is a trojan which targets computers with AwardBIOS, Microsoft Windows, and antivirus software from two Chinese companies: Rising Antivirus and Jiangmin KV Antivirus.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Mebromi installs a rootkit which infects the Master boot record.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In a December 2013 interview with *60 Minutes*, Deborah Plunkett, Information Assurance Director for the US National Security Agency claimed the NSA had uncovered and thwarted a possible BIOS attack by a foreign nation state, targeting the US financial system.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The program cited anonymous sources alleging it was a Chinese plot.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] However follow-up articles in *The Guardian,* *The Atlantic,* *Wired* and *The Register* refuted the NSA's claims.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Newer Intel platforms have Intel Boot Guard (IBG) technology enabled, this technology will check the BIOS digital signature at startup, and the IBG public key is fused into the PCH.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) supplements the BIOS in many new machines.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Initially written for the Intel Itanium architecture, UEFI is now available for x86 and Arm platforms; the specification development is driven by the Unified EFI Forum, an industry special interest group.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] EFI booting has been supported in only Microsoft Windows versions supporting GPT, the Linux kernel 2.6.1 and later, and macOS on Intel-based Macs.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As of 2014, new PC hardware predominantly ships with UEFI firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] The architecture of the rootkit safeguard can also prevent the system from running the user's own software changes, which makes UEFI controversial as a legacy BIOS replacement in the open hardware community.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] UEFI is required for devices shipping with Windows 8 and above.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Likewise, Windows 11 requires UEFI to boot, with the exception of IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] After the popularity of UEFI in 2010s, the older BIOS that supported BIOS interrupt calls was renamed to "legacy BIOS".
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Other alternatives to the functionality of the "Legacy BIOS" in the x86 world include coreboot and libreboot.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Some servers and workstations use a platform-independent Open Firmware (IEEE-1275) based on the Forth programming language; it is included with Sun's SPARC computers, IBM's RS/6000 line, and other PowerPC systems such as the CHRP motherboards, along with the x86-based OLPC XO-1.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As of at least 2015, Apple has removed legacy BIOS support from the UEFI monitor in Intel-based Macs.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] As such, the BIOS utility no longer supports the legacy option, and prints "Legacy mode not supported on this system".
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] In 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy BIOS support by 2020.
[src:uefi-firmware/bios] Since 2019, new Intel platform OEM PCs no longer support the legacy option.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:uefi-firmware/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:uefi-firmware/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The **GUID Partition Table** (**GPT**) is a standard for the layout of partition tables of a physical computer storage device, such as a hard disk drive or solid-state drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] It is part of the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) standard.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] It has several advantages over master boot record (MBR) partition tables, such as support for more than four primary partitions and 64-bit rather than 32-bit logical block addresses (LBA) for blocks on a storage device.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The larger LBA size supports larger disks.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Some BIOSes support GPT partition tables as well as MBR partition tables, in order to support larger disks than MBR partition tables can support.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] GPT uses universally unique identifiers (UUIDs), which are also known as globally unique identifiers (GUIDs), to identify partitions and partition types.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] All modern personal computer operating systems support GPT.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Some, including macOS and Microsoft Windows on the x86 architecture, support booting from GPT partitions only on systems with EFI firmware, but FreeBSD and most Linux distributions can boot from GPT partitions on systems with either the BIOS or the EFI firmware interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The Master Boot Record (MBR) partitioning scheme, widely used since the early 1980s, had limitations when it came to modern hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The available size for block addresses and related information is limited to 32 bits.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] For hard disks with 512‑byte sectors, the MBR partition table entries allow a maximum size of 2 TiB (232 × 512‑bytes) or 2.20 TB (2.20 × 1012 bytes).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] In the late 1990s, Intel developed a new partition table format as part of what eventually became the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The GUID Partition Table is specified in chapter 5 of the UEFI 2.11 specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] GPT uses 64 bits for logical block addresses, allowing a maximum disk size of 264 sectors.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] In 2010, hard-disk manufacturers introduced drives with 4,096‑byte sectors (Advanced Format).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] For compatibility with legacy hardware and software, those drives include an emulation technology (512e) that presents 512‑byte sectors to the entity accessing the hard drive, despite their underlying 4,096‑byte physical sectors.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Performance could be degraded on write operations, when the drive is forced to perform two read-modify-write operations to satisfy a single misaligned 4,096‑byte write operation.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Since April 2014, enterprise-class drives without emulation technology (4K native) have been available on the market.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Readiness of the support for 4 KB logical sectors within operating systems differs among their types, vendors and versions.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] For example, Microsoft Windows supports 4K native drives since Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 (both released in 2012) in UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Like MBR, GPT uses logical block addressing (LBA) in place of the historical cylinder-head-sector (CHS) addressing.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The protective MBR is stored at LBA 0, and the GPT header is in LBA 1.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The GPT header has a pointer to the partition table (*Partition Entry Array*), which is typically at LBA 2.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Each entry in the partition table has the same size, which is 128 or 256 or 512, etc., bytes; typically this size is 128 bytes.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The UEFI specification stipulates that a minimum of 16,384 bytes, regardless of sector size, are allocated for the Partition Entry Array.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Thus, on a disk with 512-byte sectors, at least 32 sectors are used for the Partition Entry Array, and the first usable block is at LBA 34 or higher, while on a 4,096-byte sector disk, at least 4 sectors are used for the Partition Entry Array, and the first usable block is at LBA 6 or higher.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] In addition to the primary GPT header and Partition Entry Array, stored at the beginning of the disk, there is a backup GPT header and Partition Entry Array, stored at the end of the disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The backup GPT header must be at the last block on the disk (LBA -1) and the backup Partition Entry Array is placed between the end of the last partition and the last block.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] For limited backward compatibility, the space of the legacy Master Boot Record (MBR) is still reserved in the GPT specification, but it is now used in a way that prevents MBR-based disk utilities from misrecognizing and possibly overwriting GPT disks.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] This is referred to as a *protective MBR*.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] A single partition of type EEh, encompassing the entire GPT drive (where "entire" actually means as much of the drive as can be represented in an MBR), is indicated and identifies it as GPT.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Operating systems and tools which cannot read GPT disks will generally recognize the disk as containing one partition of unknown type and no empty space, and will typically refuse to modify the disk unless the user explicitly requests and confirms the deletion of this partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Furthermore, GPT-aware OSes may check the protective MBR and if the enclosed partition type is not of type EEh or if there are multiple partitions defined on the target device, the OS may refuse to manipulate the partition table.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] If the actual size of the disk exceeds the maximum partition size representable using the legacy 32-bit LBA entries in the MBR partition table, the recorded size of this partition is clipped at the maximum, thereby ignoring the rest of the disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] This amounts to a maximum reported size of 2 TiB, assuming a disk with 512 bytes per sector (see 512e).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] It would result in 16 TiB with 4 KiB sectors (4Kn), but since many older operating systems and tools are hard coded for a sector size of 512 bytes or are limited to 32-bit calculations, exceeding the 2 TiB limit could cause compatibility problems.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] In operating systems that support GPT-based boot through BIOS services rather than EFI, the first sector may also still be used to store the first stage of the bootloader code, but modified to recognize GPT partitions.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The bootloader in the MBR must not assume a sector size of 512 bytes.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The partition table header defines the usable blocks on the disk.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] It also defines the number and size of the partition entries that make up the partition table (offsets 80 and 84 in the table).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] After the primary header and before the backup header, the Partition Entry Array describes partitions, using a minimum size of 128 bytes for each entry block.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The starting location of the array on disk, and the size of each entry, are given in the GPT header.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The first 16 bytes of each entry designate the partition type's globally unique identifier (GUID).
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] For example, the GUID for an EFI system partition is C12A7328-F81F-11D2-BA4B-00A0C93EC93B.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] The second 16 bytes are a GUID unique to the partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Then follow the starting and ending 64 bit LBAs, partition attributes, and the 36 character (max.) Unicode partition name.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] As is the nature and purpose of GUIDs and as per RFC 4122, no central registry is needed to ensure the uniqueness of the GUID partition type designators.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Windows 7 and earlier do not support UEFI on 32-bit platforms, and therefore do not allow booting from GPT partitions.
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] "Partition type GUID" means that each partition type is strictly identified by a GUID number unique to that type, and therefore partitions of the same type will all have the same "partition type GUID".
[src:uefi-firmware/guid-partition-table] Each partition also has a "partition unique GUID" as a separate entry, which as the name implies is a unique id for each partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] A **power-on self-test** (**POST**) is a process performed by firmware or software routines immediately after a computer or other digital electronic device is powered on.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] POST processes may set the initial state of the device and detect if any hardware components are non-functional.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The results of the POST may be displayed on a panel that is part of the device, output to an external device, or stored for future retrieval by a diagnostic tool.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In some computers, an indicator lamp or a speaker may be provided to show error codes as a sequence of flashes or beeps in the event that a computer display malfunctions.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] POST routines are part of a computer's **pre-boot sequence**.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] If they complete successfully, the bootstrap loader code is invoked to load an operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In IBM PC compatible computers, the main duties of POST are handled by the BIOS or UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In IBM PC compatible computers, the main duties of POST are handled by the BIOS or UEFI, which may hand some of these duties to other programs designed to initialize very specific peripheral devices, notably for video and SCSI initialization.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] These other duty-specific programs are generally known collectively as option ROMs or individually as the video BIOS, SCSI BIOS, etc.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In earlier BIOSes, up to around the turn of the millennium, the POST would perform a thorough test of all devices, including a complete memory test.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] This design by IBM was modeled after their larger mainframe systems, which would perform a complete hardware test as part of their cold-start process.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] As the PC platform evolved into more of a commodity consumer device, the mainframe and minicomputer-inspired high-reliability features such as parity memory and the thorough memory test in every POST were dropped from most models.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The exponential growth of PC memory sizes, driven by the equally exponential drop in memory prices, was also a factor in this, as the duration of a memory test using a given CPU is directly proportional to the memory size.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The original IBM PC could be equipped with as little as 16 KB of RAM and typically had between 64 and 640 KB; depending on the amount of equipped memory, the computer's 4.77 MHz 8088 required between 5 seconds and 1.5 minutes to complete the POST and there was no way to skip it.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Beginning with the IBM XT, a memory count was displayed during POST instead of a blank screen.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] A modern PC with a bus rate of around 1 GHz and a 32-bit bus might be 2000x or even 5000x faster, but might have many more gigabytes of memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] With boot times more of a concern now than in the 1980s, the 30- to 60-second memory test adds undesirable delay for a benefit of confidence that is not perceived to be worth that cost by most users.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Most clone PC BIOSes allowed the user to skip the POST RAM check by pressing a key, and more modern machines (2000s and later) often performed no RAM test at all unless it was enabled via the BIOS setup.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In addition, modern DRAM is significantly more reliable than DRAM was in the 1980s.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] During the POST, the BIOS must integrate multiple competing, changing, and even mutually exclusive standards and initiatives for the matrix of hardware and operating systems the PC is expected to support, although at most only simple memory tests and the setup screen are displayed.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The functions above are served by the POST in all BIOS versions back to the very first.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In early BIOSes, POST did not organize or select boot devices; it simply identified floppy or hard disks, which the system would always try to boot in that order.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The BIOS begins its POST when the CPU is reset.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The first memory location the CPU tries to execute is known as the reset vector.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In the case of a hard reboot, the northbridge will direct a code fetch request to the BIOS located on the system flash memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] For a warm boot, the BIOS will be located in the proper place in RAM and the northbridge will direct the reset vector call to the RAM.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In earlier PC systems, before chipsets were standard, the BIOS ROM would be located at an address range that included the reset vector, and BIOS ran directly out of ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] This is why the motherboard BIOS ROM is in segment F000 in the conventional memory map.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] During the POST flow of a contemporary BIOS, one of the first things a BIOS should do is determine the reason it is executing.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] For a cold boot, for example, it may need to execute all of its functionality.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] If, however, the system supports power-saving or quick-boot methods, the BIOS may be able to circumvent the standard POST device discovery and simply program the devices from a preloaded system device table.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] As part of the starting sequence the POST routines may display a prompt to the user for a key press to access built-in setup functions of the BIOS.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] This allows the user to set various options particular to the motherboard before the operating system is loaded.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] If no key is pressed, the POST will proceed on to the boot sequence required to load the installed operating system.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Many modern BIOS and UEFI implementations show a manufacturer's logo during POST and hide the classic text screens unless an error occurs.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The text screen can often be enabled in the BIOS settings by disabling the "Quiet Boot" option.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The original IBM BIOS made POST diagnostic information available by outputting a number to I/O port 0x80 (a screen display was not possible with some failure modes).
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Both progress indication and error codes were generated; in the case of a failure which did not generate a code, the code of the last successful operation was available to aid in diagnosing the problem.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Using a logic analyzer or a dedicated POST card‍—‌an interface card that shows port 0x80 output on a small display‍—‌a technician could determine the origin of the problem.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Once an operating system is running on the computer the code displayed by such a board may become meaningless, since some OSes, e.g.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Linux, use port 0x80 for I/O timing operations.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The actual numeric codes for the possible stages and error conditions differ from one BIOS supplier to another.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Codes for different BIOS versions from a single supplier may also vary, although many codes remain unchanged in different versions.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Later BIOSes used a sequence of beeps from the motherboard-attached PC speaker (if present and working) to signal error codes.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Some vendors developed proprietary variants or enhancements, such as MSI's D-Bracket.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] POST beep codes vary from manufacturer to manufacturer.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Information on numeric and beep codes is available from manufacturers of BIOSes and motherboards.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] There are websites which collect codes for many BIOSes.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Apple's Macintosh computers also perform a POST after a cold boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In the event of a fatal error, the Mac will not make its startup chime.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Macs made before 1987, upon failing the POST, crashed silently without playing any sound and froze, with a single hexadecimal string and a Sad Mac icon on the screen, if working.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Macs made after 1987 but before 1998, upon failing the POST, will immediately halt with a "death chime", which is a sound that varies by model; it can be a simple beep, a car crash sound, the sound of shattering glass, a short musical tone, or more.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] On the screen, if working, will be the Sad Mac icon, along with two hexadecimal strings, which can be used to identify the problem.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Some Macs made during that same time period do not use a death chime like Macs made before 1987, but retained the same format as those that used the death chimes, such as the presence of the Sad Mac icon and two hexadecimal strings on screen.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Old World Macs based on PCI architecture before 1998 don’t display a Sad Mac icon nor the hexadecimal strings on screen and only play the death chime.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] When Apple introduced the iMac in 1998, it was a radical departure from other Macs of the time.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The iMac began the production of New World Macs, as they are called; New World Macs, such as the iMac G3, Power Macintosh G3 (Blue & White), Power Mac G4 (PCI Graphics), PowerBook G3 (bronze keyboard), and PowerBook G3 (FireWire), load the Mac OS ROM from the hard drive.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In the event of an error that is not a fatal hardware error, they display the same screen as seen when holding ⌘ Command+⌥ Option+O+F at startup but with the error message instead of the "0 >" prompt.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The beep codes were revised in October 1999.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In addition, on some models, the power LED will flash in cadence.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] With the introduction of Intel-based Macs using UEFI, the startup tones were changed again.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] These tones are not present in Intel-based Macs equipped with a T2 security chip, as they handle the POST process differently from those without a T2 security chip.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The Mac transition to Apple silicon marked a radical change in the POST process in Macs.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Unlike most Intel-based Macs with UEFI, Apple silicon-based Macs use a boot ROM that loads the Low-Level Bootloader (LLB), similar to that of the firmware for the iPhone and iPad.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] No audible beep codes or tones are used to indicate hardware failures, similar to Intel-based Macs equipped with a T2 security chip.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In the event of an error that is not a fatal hardware error, an exclamation mark will be displayed on the screen or the device will go into Device Firmware Update (DFU) mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] In the event of a fatal hardware error, no audio or visual feedback is provided.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Disables and clears all DMA and interrupts.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Checks the general hardware configuration.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] If the screen remains a light gray color and the tests continue, the hardware is OK.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] If the system fails the ROM test, the screen display turns red and the system halts.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Almost all Amiga models present the same color sequence when turned on: black screen, dark gray, light gray color screens filling the entire monitor screen in a rapid sequence (Amigas usually take between 2 and 3 seconds to turn on and boot).
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] The keyboards of historical Amiga models are not proprietary as it happened in early computer ages, but more pragmatically it was based on international standard ANSI/ISO 8859-1.
[src:uefi-firmware/power-on-self-test] Many embedded systems such as those in major appliances, avionics, communications, or medical equipment have built-in self-test routines that are automatically invoked at power-on.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In particular, the MBR limits on the number and size of disk partitions (up to four primary partitions per disk, and up to 2 TB (2 × 240 bytes) per disk) are relaxed.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] More specifically, GPT allows for a maximum disk and partition size of 8 ZiB (8 × 270 bytes) with 512 byte sectors.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification only supports FAT12/16/32 partitions that are on GPT or MBR disks as well as El Torito-formatted optical discs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Although GPT is a part of the UEFI standard, it may also be usable by BIOS PCs to boot an operating system off of.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Support for GPT in Linux is enabled by turning on the option `CONFIG_EFI_PARTITION` (EFI GUID Partition Support) during kernel configuration.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This option allows Linux to recognize and use GPT disks after the system firmware passes control over the system to Linux.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For reverse compatibility, Linux can use GPT disks in BIOS-based systems for both data storage and booting, as both GRUB 2 and Linux are GPT-aware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Such a setup is usually referred to as *BIOS-GPT*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As GPT incorporates the protective MBR, a BIOS-based computer can boot from a GPT disk using a GPT-aware boot loader stored in the protective MBR's bootstrap code area.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In the case of GRUB, such a configuration requires a BIOS boot partition for GRUB to embed its second-stage code due to absence of the post-MBR gap in GPT partitioned disks (which is taken over by the GPT's *Primary Header* and *Primary Partition Table*).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Commonly 1 MB in size, this partition's Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) in GPT scheme is 21686148-6449-6E6F-744E-656564454649 and is used by GRUB only in BIOS-GPT setups.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] From GRUB's perspective, no such partition type exists in case of MBR partitioning.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This partition is not required if the system is UEFI-based because no embedding of the second-stage code is needed in that case.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI systems can access GPT disks and boot directly from them, which allows Linux to use UEFI boot methods.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Booting Linux from GPT disks on UEFI systems involves creation of an EFI system partition (ESP), which contains UEFI applications such as bootloaders, operating system kernels, and utility software.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Such a setup is usually referred to as *UEFI-GPT*, while ESP is recommended to be at least 512 MB in size and formatted with a FAT32 filesystem for maximum compatibility.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For backward compatibility, some UEFI implementations also support booting from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In that case, booting Linux on UEFI systems is the same as on legacy BIOS-based systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Windows 11, 64-bit versions of Windows Vista SP1/SP2 and 7, and both 32-bit and 64-bit versions of Windows 8, 8.1, and 10 can boot from a GPT disk that is larger than 2 TB.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] EFI defines two types of services: *boot services* and *runtime services*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Boot services are available only while the firmware owns the platform (i.e., before the `ExitBootServices()` call), and they include text and graphical consoles on various devices, and bus, block and file services.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Runtime services are still accessible while the operating system is running; they include services such as date, time and NVRAM access.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI variables provide a way to store data, in particular non-volatile data.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some UEFI variables are shared between platform firmware and operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Variable namespaces are identified by GUIDs, and variables are key/value pairs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] after a crash for the operating system to retrieve after a reboot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI executes independent programs known as UEFI applications, which are stored as files on the EFI system partition.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These can be launched via the UEFI Shell, the firmware boot manager, or other UEFI applications, and may be developed independently of the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A type of UEFI application is an OS boot loader such as GRUB, rEFInd, systemd-boot, and Windows Boot Manager, which loads some OS files into memory and executes them.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Also, an OS boot loader can provide a user interface to allow the selection of another UEFI application to run.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Utilities like the UEFI Shell are also UEFI applications.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] EFI defines protocols as a set of software interfaces used for communication between two binary modules.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] All EFI drivers must provide services to others via protocols.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI Protocols are similar to the BIOS interrupt calls.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to standard instruction set architecture-specific device drivers, EFI provides for an ISA-independent device driver stored in non-volatile memory as *EFI byte code* or *EBC*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] System firmware has an interpreter for EBC images.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In that sense, EBC is analogous to Open Firmware, the ISA-independent firmware used in PowerPC-based Apple Macintosh and Sun Microsystems SPARC computers, among others.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some architecture-specific (non-EFI Byte Code) EFI drivers for some device types can have interfaces for use by the OS.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This allows the OS to rely on EFI for drivers to perform basic graphics and network functions before, and if, operating-system-specific drivers are loaded.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In other cases, the EFI driver can be filesystem drivers that allow for booting from other types of disk volumes.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Examples include *efifs* for 37 file systems (based on GRUB2 code), used by Rufus for chain-loading NTFS ESPs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI 1.0 specification defined a UGA (Universal Graphic Adapter) protocol as a way to support graphics features.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI did not include UGA and replaced it with GOP (Graphics Output Protocol).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI 2.1 defined a "Human Interface Infrastructure" (HII) to manage user input, localized strings, fonts, and forms (in the HTML sense).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These enable original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) or independent BIOS vendors (IBVs) to design graphical interfaces for pre-boot configuration.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI uses UTF-16 to encode strings by default; since at least UEFI 2.4, it allows using ASCII to encode ASCII-only strings.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most early UEFI firmware implementations were console-based.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Today many UEFI firmware implementations are GUI-based.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] An EFI system partition, often abbreviated to ESP, is a data storage device partition that is used in computers adhering to the UEFI specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Accessed by the UEFI firmware when a computer is powered up, it stores UEFI applications and the files these applications need to run, including operating system boot loaders.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Supported partition table schemes include MBR and GPT, as well as El Torito volumes on optical discs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For use on ESPs, UEFI defines a specific version of the FAT file system, which is maintained as part of the UEFI specification and independently from the original FAT specification, encompassing the FAT32, FAT16 and FAT12 file systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The ESP also provides space for a boot sector as part of the backward BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Computers are started up by a process which has been called booting: the computer loads its operating software by means of a very small program built into the hardware, which typically loads a program, still small, to load and start the operating system (OS).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the legacy PC BIOS, UEFI does not rely on boot sectors on the computer's data storage, defining instead a boot manager as part of the UEFI specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When a computer is powered on, the boot manager checks the boot configuration and, based on its settings, then executes the specified OS boot loader or operating system kernel.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The boot configuration is defined by variables stored in the computer's persistent NVRAM storage, including variables that indicate the file system paths to OS loaders or OS kernels.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] OS boot loaders can be automatically detected by UEFI, which enables easy booting from removable devices such as USB flash drives.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This automated detection relies on standardized file paths to the OS boot loader, with the path varying depending on the computer architecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The format of the file path is defined as <EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>\EFI\BOOT\BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI; for example, the file path to the OS loader on an x86-64 system is \efi\boot\bootx64.efi, and \efi\boot\bootaa64.efi on ARM64 architecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Booting UEFI systems from GPT-partitioned disks is commonly called *UEFI-GPT booting*, although the UEFI specification requires MBR partition tables to be fully supported.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some UEFI firmware implementations immediately switch to BIOS-based CSM booting depending on the type of the boot disk's partition table, effectively preventing UEFI booting from an EFI System Partition on MBR-partitioned disks; such a boot scheme is commonly called *UEFI-MBR*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It is also common for a boot manager to have a textual user interface to allow the user to select the desired OS (or setup utility) from a list of available boot options.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On PC platforms, firmware supporting UEFI boot is often referred to as a "UEFI BIOS", though some newer x86 platforms exclude CSM support entirely.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] To ensure backward compatibility, UEFI firmware implementations on PC-class machines could support booting in legacy BIOS mode from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In this scenario, booting is performed in the same way as on legacy BIOS-based systems, by ignoring the partition table and relying on the content of a boot sector.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Compatibility Support Module allows legacy operating systems and some legacy option ROMs that do not support UEFI to still be used.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It also provides required legacy System Management Mode (SMM) functionality (CompatibilitySmm) in addition to features provided by the UEFI SMM.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] An example of such a legacy SMM functionality is providing USB legacy support for keyboard and mouse, by emulating their classic PS/2 counterparts.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In November 2017, Intel announced that it planned to phase out support CSM for client platforms by 2020.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In July 2022, Kaspersky Labs published information regarding a Rootkit designed to chain boot malicious code on machines using Intel's H81 chipset and the Compatibility Support Module of affected motherboards.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In August 2023, Intel announced that it planned to phase out CSM support for server platforms by 2024.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification includes support for booting over network via the Preboot Execution Environment (PXE).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] PXE booting network protocols include Internet Protocol (IPv4 and IPv6), User Datagram Protocol (UDP), Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) and iSCSI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] OS images can be remotely stored on storage area networks (SANs), with Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) and Fibre Channel over Ethernet (FCoE) as supported protocols for accessing the SANs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.5 of the UEFI specification adds support for accessing boot images over HTTP.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification defines a Secure Boot that can secure the boot process by preventing the loading of UEFI drivers or OS boot loaders that are not signed with an acceptable digital signature.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When Secure Boot is enabled, it is initially placed in "setup" mode, which allows a public key known as the "platform key" (PK) to be written to the firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once the key is written, Secure Boot enters "User" mode, where only UEFI drivers and OS boot loaders signed with the platform key can be loaded by the firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Additional "key exchange keys" (KEK) can be added to a database stored in memory to allow other certificates to be used, but they must still have a connection to the private portion of the platform key.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Secure Boot can also be placed in "Custom" mode, where additional public keys can be added to the system that do not match the private key.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As of January 2025, FreeBSD support is in its planning stage.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI provides a shell environment, which can be used to execute other UEFI applications, including UEFI boot loaders.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Source code for a UEFI shell can be downloaded from the Intel's TianoCore UDK/EDK2 project.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A pre-built ShellBinPkg is also available.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Shell v2 works best in UEFI 2.3+ systems and is recommended over Shell v1 in those systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Shell v1 should work in all UEFI systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Methods used for launching UEFI shell depend on the manufacturer and model of the system motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some of them already provide a direct option in firmware setup for launching, e.g. compiled x86-64 version of the shell needs to be made available as `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/SHELLX64.EFI`.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some other systems have an already embedded UEFI shell which can be launched by appropriate key press combinations.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For other systems, the solution is either creating an appropriate USB flash drive or adding manually (`bcfg`) a boot option associated with the compiled version of shell.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The following is a list of commands supported by the EFI shell.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Extensions to UEFI can be loaded from virtually any non-volatile storage device attached to the computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, an original equipment manufacturer (OEM) can distribute systems with an EFI system partition on the hard drive, which would add additional functions to the standard UEFI firmware stored on the motherboard's ROM.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI Capsule defines a firmware-to-OS firmware update interface.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Windows 8, Windows 8.1, Windows 10, and Fwupd for Linux each support the UEFI Capsule.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Like BIOS, UEFI initializes and tests system hardware components, and then loads the boot loader from a mass storage device or through a network connection.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In x86 systems, the UEFI firmware is usually stored in the NOR flash chip of the motherboard, and the boot process is more complex, for example PCI Express devices detection and initialization.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In some ARM-based Android and Windows Phone devices, the UEFI boot loader is stored in the eMMC or eUFS flash memory.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Starting from the 10th Gen Intel Core, Intel no longer provides Legacy Video BIOS for the iGPU (Intel Graphics Technology).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Legacy boot with those CPUs requires a Legacy Video BIOS, which can still be provided by a video card.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This is the first stage of the UEFI boot but may have platform specific binary code that precedes it.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] (e.g., Intel ME, AMD PSP, CPU microcode).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It consists of minimal code written in assembly language for the specific architecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It initializes a temporary memory (often CPU cache-as-RAM (CAR), or SoC on-chip boot processor) and serves as the system's software root of trust with the option of verifying PEI before hand-off.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The second stage of UEFI boot consists of a dependency-aware dispatcher that loads and runs PEI modules (PEIMs) to handle early hardware initialization tasks such as main memory initialization (initialize memory controller and DRAM) and firmware recovery operations.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Additionally, it is responsible for discovery of the current boot mode and handling many ACPI S3 operations.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In the case of ACPI S3 resume, it is responsible for restoring many hardware registers to a pre-sleep state.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Initialization at this stage involves creating data structures in memory and establishing default values within these structures.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This stage has several components including PEI foundation, PEIMs and PPI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Due to less resources available in this stage, this stage must be minimal and do minimal preparations for the next stage, DXE, which is richer.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] After SEC phase hand off, platform responsibility is taken by PEI Foundation.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This component is responsible for invoking PEIMs and managing their dependencies.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These are minimal PEI drivers that are responsible for initialization of hardware components, such as permanent memory, CPU, chipset and motherboard.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Each of the PEIMs have single responsibilities and focus on single initialization.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These drivers come from different vendors.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This is a data structure that composed of GUID pairs of pointers.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] PPIs are discovered by PEIMs through PEI services.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] After minimal initialization of the system for DXE, PEI foundation locates and passes control to DXE.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The PEI foundation dispatches DXE foundation through special PPI called IPL (Initial Program Load).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This stage consists of C modules and a dependency-aware dispatcher.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] With main memory now available, CPU, chipset, mainboard and other I/O devices are initialized in DXE and BDS.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Initialization at this stage involves assigning EFI device paths to the hardware connected to the motherboard, and transferring configuration data to the hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In this stage, boot devices are initialized, UEFI drivers or Option ROMs of PCI devices are executed according to architecturally defined variables called **NVRAM**, and the operating system boot loaders (such as Windows Boot Manager) are started.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This is the stage between boot device selection and hand-off to the OS.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] At this point one may enter a UEFI shell, or execute a UEFI application such as the OS boot loader.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI hands off to the operating system (OS) after ExitBootServices() is executed.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A UEFI compatible OS is now responsible for exiting boot services triggering the firmware to unload all no longer needed code and data, leaving only runtime services code/data, e.g.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A typical modern OS will prefer to use its own programs (such as kernel drivers) to control hardware devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When a legacy OS is used, CSM will handle this call ensuring the system is compatible with legacy BIOS expectations.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel's implementation of EFI is the *Intel Platform Innovation Framework*, codenamed *Tiano*.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Tiano runs on Intel's XScale, Itanium, IA-32 and x86-64 processors, and is proprietary software, although a portion of the code has been released under the BSD license or Eclipse Public License (EPL) as TianoCore EDK II.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] TianoCore can be used as a payload for coreboot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Phoenix Technologies' implementation of UEFI is branded as SecureCore Technology (SCT).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] American Megatrends offers its own UEFI firmware implementation known as Aptio, while Insyde Software offers InsydeH2O, and Byosoft offers ByoCore.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In December 2018, Microsoft released an open source version of its TianoCore EDK2-based UEFI implementation from the Surface line, Project Mu.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] An implementation of the UEFI API was introduced into the Universal Boot Loader (Das U-Boot) in 2017.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On the ARMv8 architecture Linux distributions use the U-Boot UEFI implementation in conjunction with GNU GRUB for booting (e.g.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SUSE Linux), the same holds true for OpenBSD.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For booting from iSCSI iPXE can be used as a UEFI application loaded by U-Boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel's first Itanium workstations and servers, released in 2000, implemented EFI 1.02.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Hewlett-Packard's first Itanium 2 systems, released in 2002, implemented EFI 1.10.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These systems were able to boot Windows, Linux, FreeBSD and HP-UX.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] OpenVMS added UEFI capability in June 2003.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In January 2006, Apple Inc. shipped its first Intel-based Macintosh computers.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These systems used EFI instead of Open Firmware, which had been used on its previous PowerPC-based systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On 5 April 2006, Apple first released Boot Camp, which produces a Windows drivers disk and a non-destructive partitioning tool to allow the installation of Windows XP or Vista without requiring a reinstallation of Mac OS X (now macOS).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A firmware update was also released that added BIOS compatibility to its EFI implementation.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Subsequent Macintosh models shipped with the newer firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] During 2005, more than one million Intel systems shipped with Intel's implementation of UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] New mobile, desktop and server products, using Intel's implementation of UEFI, started shipping in 2006.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For instance, boards that use the Intel 945 chipset series use Intel's UEFI firmware implementation.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Since 2005, EFI has also been implemented on non-PC architectures, such as embedded systems based on XScale cores.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EDK (EFI Developer Kit) includes an NT32 target, which allows EFI firmware and EFI applications to run within a Windows application.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, no direct hardware access is allowed by EDK NT32.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This means only a subset of EFI application and drivers can be executed by the EDK NT32 target.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2008, more x86-64 systems adopted UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] While many of these systems still allow booting only the BIOS-based OSes via the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) (thus not appearing to the user to be UEFI-based), other systems started to allow booting UEFI-based OSes.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, IBM x3450 server, MSI motherboards with ClickBIOS and HP EliteBook Notebook PCs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2009, IBM shipped System x machines (x3550 M2, x3650 M2, iDataPlex dx360 M2) and BladeCenter HS22 with UEFI capability.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Dell shipped PowerEdge T610, R610, R710, M610 and M710 servers with UEFI capability.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] More commercially available systems are mentioned in a UEFI whitepaper.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2011, major vendors (such as ASRock, Asus, Gigabyte, and MSI) launched several consumer-oriented motherboards using the Intel 6-series LGA 1155 chipset and AMD 9 Series AM3+ chipsets with UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] With the release of Windows 8 in October 2012, Microsoft's certification requirements now require that computers include firmware that implements the UEFI specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Furthermore, if the computer supports the "Connected Standby" feature of Windows 8 (which allows devices to have power management comparable to smartphones, with an almost instantaneous return from standby mode), then the firmware is not permitted to contain a Compatibility Support Module (CSM).
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As such, systems that support Connected Standby are incapable of booting Legacy BIOS operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy PC BIOS support from all its products by 2020, in favor of UEFI Class 3.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] By 2019, all computers based on Intel platforms no longer have legacy PC BIOS support.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A operating system that can be booted from (U)EFI is called a (U)EFI-aware operating system, defined by (U)EFI specification.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Here the term *booted from a (U)EFI* means directly booting the system using a (U)EFI operating system loader stored on any storage device.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The default location for the operating system loader is `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/BOOT/BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI`, where short name of the machine type can be `IA32`, `X64`, `IA64`, `ARM` or `AA64`.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some operating systems vendors may have their own boot loaders.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] They may also change the default boot location.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI implementation flaws have been exploited to gain persistence, the ability to maintain malicious access to a compromised system even after system reboot, operating system reinstallation, and even partial physical part replacement, such as of corrupted PCI persistent flash storage.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] There were vulnerabilities in 2023 even with Secure Boot enabled.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2023 Microsoft published a warning about BlackLotus UEFI malware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Numerous digital rights activists have protested UEFI.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Minnich, a co-author of coreboot, and Cory Doctorow, a digital rights activist, have criticized UEFI as an attempt to remove the ability of the user to truly control the computer.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Critics, such as coreboot co-author Ronald G.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Minnich, argue that UEFI maintains the historic arrangement of requiring two separate drivers—one for the firmware and one for the operating system—for most hardware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Open-source project TianoCore also provides UEFIs.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] TianoCore lacks the specialized firmware drivers and modules that initialize chipset functions, but TianoCore is one of many payload options of coreboot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The development of coreboot requires cooperation from chipset manufacturers to provide the specifications needed to develop initialization drivers.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2011, Microsoft announced that computers certified to run its Windows 8 operating system had to ship with Microsoft's public key enrolled and Secure Boot enabled, which implies that using UEFI is a requirement for these devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Following the announcement, critics and free-software/open-source advocates, including the Free Software Foundation, expressed concern that Microsoft might use the Secure Boot functionality of UEFI to restrict the installation of alternative operating systems such as Linux.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Microsoft denied that the Secure Boot requirement was intended to serve as a form of lock-in and clarified its requirements by stating that x86-based systems certified for Windows 8 must allow Secure Boot to enter custom mode or be disabled, but not on systems using the ARM architecture.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Windows 10 allows OEMs to decide whether or not Secure Boot can be managed by users of their x86 systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Other developers raised concerns about the legal and practical issues of implementing support for Secure Boot on Linux systems in general.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Other developers suggested that signed builds of Linux with another key could be provided, but noted that it would be difficult to persuade OEMs to ship their computers with the required key alongside the Microsoft key.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Several major Linux distributions have developed different implementations for Secure Boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Garrett himself developed a minimal bootloader known as a shim, which is a precompiled, signed bootloader that allows the user to individually trust keys provided by Linux distributions.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] That also allows users to build their own kernels and use custom kernel modules as well, without the need to reconfigure the system.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Fedora also uses shim, but requires that both the kernel and its modules be signed as well. shim has Machine Owner Key (MOK) that can be used to sign locally compiled kernels and other software not signed by distribution maintainer, without changing the Secure Boot mode to setup mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In Windows, if Secure Boot is enabled, all kernel drivers must be digitally signed; non-WHQL drivers may be refused to load.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In February 2013, another Red Hat developer attempted to submit a patch to the Linux kernel that would allow it to parse Microsoft's authenticode signing using a master X.509 key embedded in PE files signed by Microsoft.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, the proposal was criticized by Linux creator Linus Torvalds, who argued that Red Hat was accommodating Microsoft's control over the Secure Boot infrastructure.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On 26 March 2013, the Spanish free-software development group Hispalinux filed a formal complaint with the European Commission, contending that Microsoft's Secure Boot requirements on OEM systems were "obstructive" and anti-competitive.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] At the Black Hat conference in August 2013, a group of security researchers presented a series of exploits in specific vendor implementations of UEFI that could be used to exploit Secure Boot.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In August 2016 it was reported that two security researchers had found the "golden key" security key Microsoft uses in signing operating systems.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Technically, no key was exposed, but an exploitable binary signed by the key was.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This allows software to execute as though it were signed by Microsoft, presenting potential risks for rootkit and bootkit attacks.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This also complicates remediation efforts, since a patch can potentially be downgraded by replacing it with the signed exploitable binary.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Microsoft stated that the vulnerability only affects ARM architecture and Windows RT devices and released two updates; however, reports noted that these updates do not completely prevent exploitation because fully resolving the vulnerability would require key replacements in end-user firmware.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On 1 March 2023, researchers from ESET reported discovering "BlackLotus", described as the first active UEFI bootkit capable of bypassing UEFI Secure Boot by exploiting the limitations of the previous security updates.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In August 2024, the Windows 11 and Windows 10 security updates applied the Secure Boot Advanced Targeting (SBAT) settings to device's UEFI NVRAM, which caused some Linux distributions to fail to load.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SBAT is a protocol that supported in new versions of Windows Boot Manager and shim, which refuse buggy or vulnerable intermediate bootloaders (usually older versions of Windows Boot Manager and GRUB) to load in the boot process.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In June 2025, LWN.net reported that the Microsoft UEFI CA 2011 certificate will be expired on June 27, 2026, which may refuse some Linux to load if Secure Boot is enabled.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, in TianoCore EDK II as well as many commercial UEFI implementations (such as AMI Aptio), time/date check for Secure Boot certificate is usually disabled by default.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Many Linux distributions support UEFI Secure Boot as of January 2025, such as RHEL (RHEL 7 and later), CentOS (CentOS 7 and later), Ubuntu, Fedora, Debian (Debian 10 and later), OpenSUSE, and SUSE Linux Enterprise.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A number of technical issues have been reported regarding specific implementations of UEFI firmware in commercial devices.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Similar operational difficulties were reported regarding several Toshiba laptop models where specific firmware certificates required for Secure Boot operation were missing.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In January 2013, a firmware issue was publicized regarding the UEFI implementation on certain Samsung laptops, which rendered the devices completely inoperable after a Linux distribution was installed in UEFI mode.
[src:uefi-firmware/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] His analysis concluded that the associated kernel module caused kernel message dumps to be written to the firmware storage space, executing the failure state.
